<section>
  <title>Continuous Functions</title>

<p><xref ref="def-cts" /></p>

<p>Note here that the value of <m>\delta</m> depends on both <m>\epsilon</m> and <m>c</m>, so we could write <m>\delta=\delta(\epsilon,c)</m>.</p>

<p><xref ref="def-ctsonA" /></p>

<!-- <p workspace="4in"></p> -->
<!-- picture that goes with continuous function a x=c -->
</section>

<section>
<example>
  <title><m>f(x)=7x+5</m> is continuous at <m>x=2</m></title>
  <p>
    Let <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m> be given.  According to <xref ref="def-cts" /> we need to show there is a <m>\delta &gt; 0</m> for which <m>|x-2| &lt; \delta</m> implies <m>|f(x)-f(2)|=|(7x+5)-(7 \cdot 2+5)| &lt; \epsilon</m>.
  </p>
  <!-- 
  <p workspace="2in">
    SCRATCH WORK
  </p>
-->
  <p>
    Choose <m>\delta = \min\{1, \epsilon/7\}</m> and consider <m>x \in \mathbb{R}</m> for which <m>|x-2| &lt; \delta</m>.  Then we can say
    <md>
      <mrow>|(7x+5)-(7 \cdot 2+5)| \amp = |7x+5-19| </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = |7x-14| </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = |7(x-2)| </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = 7 \cdot |x-2|</mrow>
      <mrow> \amp &lt; 7 \cdot \epsilon/7 \text{ because } |x-2| &lt; \epsilon/7</mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = \epsilon</mrow>.
    </md>
    This shows <m>f(x)=7x+5</m> is continuous at <m>x=2</m>.
  </p>
</example>

<example>
  <title><m>f(x)=7x+5</m> is continuous on <m>\mathbb{R}</m></title>
  <p>
    Let <m>c \in \mathbb{R}</m>, and let <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m> be given.  According to <xref ref="def-cts" /> we need to show there is a <m>\delta &gt; 0</m> for which <m>|x-c| &lt; \delta</m> implies <m>|f(x)-f(c)|=|(7x+5)-(7 \cdot c+5)| &lt; \epsilon</m>.
  </p>
  <!-- 
  <p workspace="2in">
    SCRATCH WORK
  </p>
-->
  <p>
    Choose <m>\delta = \epsilon/7</m> and consider <m>x \in \mathbb{R}</m> for which <m>|x-c| &lt; \delta</m>.  Then we can say
    <md>
      <mrow>|(7x+5)-(7 \cdot c+5)| \amp = |7x+5-7c-5| </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = |7x-7c| </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = |7(x-c)| </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = 7 \cdot |x-c|</mrow>
      <mrow> \amp &lt; 7 \cdot \epsilon/7 \text{ because } |x-c| &lt; \epsilon/7</mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = \epsilon</mrow>.
    </md>
    This shows <m>f(x)=7x+5</m> is continuous at <m>x=c</m>.  Since the choice of <m>x=c</m> was an arbitrary real number, the above shows that <m>f(x)=7x+5</m> is continuous at all reals.
  </p>
</example>

</section>


<section>

<example>
  <title><m>f(x)=x^2</m> is continuous at <m>x=5</m></title>
  <p>
    Let <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m> be given.  According to <xref ref="def-cts" /> we need to show there is a <m>\delta &gt; 0</m> for which <m>|x-5| &lt; \delta</m> implies <m>|f(x)-f(2)|=|x^2-25| &lt; \epsilon</m>.
  </p>
<!-- 
  <p workspace="2in">
    SCRATCH WORK
  </p>
-->
  <p>
    Choose <m>\delta = \min\{1, \epsilon/11\}</m> and consider <m>x \in \mathbb{R}</m> for which <m>|x-5| &lt; \delta</m>.  Then because <m>|x-5| &lt; \delta \leq 1</m> we know <m>-1 &lt; x-5 &lt; 1</m> and <m>9 &lt; x+5 &lt; 11</m> so <m>|x+5| &lt; 11</m>.  We can also say
    <md>
      <mrow>|x^2-25| \amp = |x-5| \cdot |x+5| </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp &lt; |x-5| \cdot 11 \text{ because } x-5| &lt; 1</mrow>
      <mrow> \amp &lt; \epsilon/11 \cdot 11 \text{ because } x-5| &lt; \epsilon/11</mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = \epsilon</mrow>.
    </md>
    This shows <m>f(x)=x^2</m> is continuous at <m>x=5</m>.
  </p>
</example>
</section>

<section xml:id="sec-">
  <title>The Squaring Function is Continuous</title>

<example>
  <title><m>f(x)=x^2</m> is continuous on <m>\mathbb{R}</m></title>
  <p>
    We need to show <m>f(x)</m> is continuous at every real number.  Let <m>c \in \mathbb{R}</m>.  We will show that <m>f(x)</m> is continuous at <m>x=c</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Let <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m> be given.  According to <xref ref="def-cts" /> we need to show there is a <m>\delta &gt; 0</m> for which <m>|x-c| &lt; \delta</m> implies <m>|f(x)-f(c)|=|x^2-c^2| &lt; \epsilon</m>.
  </p>
  <!-- 
  <p workspace="3in">
    SCRATCH WORK
  </p>
  -->
  <p>
    Choose <m>\delta = \min\{1, \epsilon/(1+2|c|)\}</m> and consider <m>x \in \mathbb{R}</m> for which <m>|x-c| &lt; \delta</m>.  Then because <m>|x-c| &lt; \delta \leq 1</m> we know <m>-1 &lt; x-c &lt; 1</m> and <m>2c-1 &lt; x+c &lt; 2c+1</m> so <m>|x+c| &lt; \max\{|2c \pm 1|\}</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
     Notice that if <m>c \geq 0</m> then <m>|2c-1| &lt; |2c+1|=2c+1=2|c|+1</m>.  On the other hand, if <m>c \leq 0</m>m then <m>|2c-1| \geq |2c+1|</m> and <m>|2c-1|=|2(-|c|)-1|=|2\cdot|c|+1|=2|c|+1</m> so <m>|2c+1| \leq 2|c|+1</m>.  Therefore, regardless of the sign of <m>c \in \mathbb{R}</m> we can say <m>\max\{|2c \pm 1|\} \leq 2|c|+1</m>.  It follows that if <m>|x-c| &lt; 1</m> then <m>|x+c| &lt; 2|c|+1</m>.
  </p>  
  <p>
    With this established, choose <m>x \in \mathbb{R}</m> so that <m>|x-c| &lt; \delta</m>. Then
    <md>
      <mrow>|x^2-c^2| \amp = |x-c| \cdot |x+c| </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp &lt; |x-c| \cdot (2|c|+1) \text{ because } |x-5| &lt; 1</mrow>
      <mrow> \amp &lt; \epsilon/(2|c|+1) \cdot (2|c|+1) \text{ because } |x-c| &lt; \epsilon/(2|c|+1)</mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = \epsilon</mrow>.
    </md>
    This shows <m>f(x)=x^2</m> is continuous at <m>x=c</m>.  Since <m>c</m> was arbitrary, this shows that <m>f(x)=x^2</m> is continuous on all <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.
  </p>
</example>

</section>

<section>

<theorem xml:id="thm-altcts">
  <title>Alternate Characterization of Continuity</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>f:A \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</m> and let <m>c \in A</m>.  The function <m>f</m> is continuous at <m>c \in A</m> if and only if one of (<xref ref="thm-altcts-item1" />), (<xref ref="thm-altcts-item2" />), or (<xref ref="thm-altcts-item3" />) below holds:
      <ol>
        <li xml:id="thm-altcts-item1">
          <p>
            for all <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m> there is a <m>\delta &gt; 0</m> such that <m>|x-c| &lt; \delta</m> (and <m>x \in A</m>) implies <m>|f(x)-f(c)| &lt; \epsilon</m>;
          </p>
        </li>
        <li xml:id="thm-altcts-item2">
          <p>
            For all <m>\epsilon</m>-neighborhoods <m>V_{\epsilon}(f(c))</m> of <m>f(c)</m> there exists a <m>\delta</m>-neighborhood <m>V_{\delta}(c)</m> of <m>c</m> with the property that for <m>x \in V_{\delta}(c) \cap A</m> we have <m>f(x) \in V_{\epsilon}(f(c))</m>; and,
          </p>
        </li>
        <li xml:id="thm-altcts-item3">
          <p>
            For all <m>(x_n) \subset A</m> with <m>(x_n)</m> converging to <m>c \in A</m> it follows that <m>(f(x_n))</m> converges to <m>f(c)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li xml:id="thm-altcts-item4">
          <p>
            If <m>c</m> is a limit point of <m>A</m>, the previous three statement are equivalent to  <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \rightarrow c} f(x)=f(c)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>
</theorem>

<proof>
  <p>
    ( (<xref ref="thm-altcts-item1" />) if and only if (<xref ref="thm-altcts-item2" />) ) 
  </p>
  <p>
    Statement (<xref ref="thm-altcts-item1" />) is the definition of continuity at the point <m>x \in A</m>, and (<xref ref="thm-altcts-item2" />) is its translation into topological terms.  This establishes the equivalence.
  </p>
  <p>
    ( (<xref ref="thm-altcts-item1" />) if and only if (<xref ref="thm-altcts-item3" />) )
  </p>
  <p>
    We'll prove (<xref ref="thm-altcts-item3" />) implies (<xref ref="thm-altcts-item1" />) by contradiction.  Assume (<xref ref="thm-altcts-item3" />), and also assume that (<xref ref="thm-altcts-item1" />) is not true.  That is, assume there is an <m>\epsilon_0 &gt; 0</m> such that for all <m>\delta &gt; 0</m> there is an <m>x \in A</m> with <m>|x-c| &lt; \delta</m> where <m>|f(x)-f(c)| &gt; \epsilon_0</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Consider <m>\delta_n=1/n</m>.  Fix <m>n</m>.  For that <m>n</m>, there is a point in <m>V_{\delta_n}(c) \cap A</m>, call the point <m>x_n</m>, at which <m>|f(x_n)-f(c)| &gt; epsilon_0</m>.  For each <m>n</m>, find the analogous point <m>x_n</m> with this property and we get a sequence <m>(x_n) \subset A</m> that converges to <m>c</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Notice that this sequence was constructed so it has the property that the sequence of values <m>(f(x_n))</m> does not converge to <m>f(c)</m>.  This contradicts (<xref ref="thm-altcts-item3" />).
  </p>
  <p>
    If follows that (<xref ref="thm-altcts-item1" />) must be true.  Hence (<xref ref="thm-altcts-item3" />) implies (<xref ref="thm-altcts-item1" />).
  </p>
  <p>
    We prove the reverse implication directly.
  </p>
  <p>
    Let <m>(x_n) \subset A</m> be a sequence that converges to <m>c</m>.  We must show that the sequence <m>(f(x_n))</m> converges to <m>f(c)</m>.  Let <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m> be given.
  </p>
  <p>
    By (<xref ref="thm-altcts-item1" />), we know there is a <m>\delta &gt; 0</m> such that if <m>|x-c| &lt; \delta</m> and <m>x \in A</m> then <m>|f(x)-f(c)| &lt; \epsilon</m>.  Since <m>(x_n)</m> converges to <m>c</m> we know there is an <m>N=N(\epsilon)</m> such that if <m>n &gt; N</m>, then <m>|x_n-c| &lt; \delta</m>.  For the same <m>n</m>, it follows that <m>|f(x_n)-f(c)| &lt; \epsilon</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    This proves (<xref ref="thm-altcts-item3" />) holds and establishes <xref ref="thm-altcts-item1" /> if and only if <xref ref="thm-altcts-item3" />.
  </p>
  <p>
    ( (<xref ref="thm-altcts-item1" />) if and only if (<xref ref="thm-altcts-item4" />) )
  </p>
  <p>
    This can be established by noting that the difference between (<xref ref="thm-altcts-item1" />) and the functional limit of (<xref ref="thm-altcts-item4" />) is the case <m>x=c \in V_{\delta}(c) \cap A</m>.  When <m>x=c</m>, we get <m>f(x)=f(c)</m> so that <m>f(c) \in V_{\epsilon}(f(c))</m>.
  </p>
</proof>
</section>


